article.description: Kevin Garnett tied his season high with 34 points Monday night to lead Minnesota to a bruising 106-95 victory over the San Antonio Spurs, the Timberwolves' sixth straight win.
article.headline: T-Wolves get rough for ninth win in 11 games
article.linkText: Garnett lights up Spurs in bruising battle
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- If it's January, the Minnesota Timberwolves must be playing well.
Garnett

Kevin Garnett tied his season high with 34 points Monday night to lead the Timberwolves to a bruising 106-95 victory over the San Antonio Spurs, Minnesota's sixth straight win. Garnett grabbed 10 rebounds and shot 14-for-19 from the floor for the Wolves, who've won nine of 11. "I don't want to jump the gun and say we're jelling,'' Garnett said, "but we're moving in the right direction.'' Wally Szczerbiak had 17 points in his first start since Nov. 16 for the Wolves, who outscored the Spurs 52-32 in the paint with San Antonio center David Robinson absent. Tony Parker scored 19 points and Tim Duncan added 17 points and 10 rebounds for the Spurs, beaten for just the second time in eight games. Malik Rose added 13 points and 11 rebounds. "They stifled us in every way,'' San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said. "They were full of intensity, playing hard, hitting the boards.'' Minnesota rallied to win Friday against the Los Angeles Clippers after trailing by 16 in the third quarter, and the Wolves overcame a 15-point halftime hole at Washington on Saturday. Injuries prevented them from finding a rhythm in the season's first two months, but now they're rolling with everyone other than Terrell Brandon and Felipe Lopez healthy. It's just that time of year. In 2002, they surged to a 30-10 record with a big start to the new year, and in 2001 they took an 11-game winning streak into the All-Star break. "We've just got to carry it through the All-Star break,'' Szczerbiak said. "We've just got to learn from previous years when we haven't carried it through the All-Star break.'' After clinging to the eighth spot in the Western Conference for most of the season, Minnesota suddenly finds itself in fifth -- just 1½ games behind San Antonio and Portland. The Timberwolves play their next five games against winning teams -- including two against Dallas, owner of the league's best record. No surprise, then, that the Wolves treated this as a big one. Their matchups with the Spurs often look more like football, and Monday was no different. Both teams grew increasingly frustrated with the officiating, often taking it out on each other. A body was on the floor on nearly every possession. The Spurs led by as many as nine in the second quarter, when most of the calls were going against Minnesota. "We could've got extremely frustrated,'' coach Flip Saunders said. "We had a lot of good play from a lot of people.'' Minnesota is 7-1 with Rod Strickland starting at point guard, and he scored 10 points in nine minutes before leaving with a strained left groin late in the second quarter. He was to be re-evaluated Tuesday. Troy Hudson, the starter for the first 37 games before spraining his ankle, scored only three points in 30 minutes but helped hold Parker to five second-half points as the Wolves pulled away. They started a 12-0 run late in the third and built a 100-80 lead on Kendall Gill's bank shot with 4½ minutes remaining. San Antonio scored 13 straight points to pull to 100-93 with 1:28 left, but the Spurs couldn't get closer. "They were the better team tonight,'' said Duncan, a bit testy. "They had better energy, better focus.'' The Spurs committed 20 turnovers. "We didn't help Tim out,'' Parker said. "It's hard to win when you don't take care of the ball.'' Szczerbiak, who came off the bench in his first 10 games back from a toe injury that kept him out for the better part of three months, started at shooting guard because Gill didn't arrive at the arena until shortly before tipoff. Gill, who was returning from a relative's funeral, scored 12 points. "Early in the year in practice, the team is trying to get into a rhythm. Chemistry is still developing,'' Garnett said. "What you're seeing is a combination of all of that coming together.'' Game notes
With other events scheduled at the SBC Center, San Antonio plays its next eight on the road and won't have a home game for more than three weeks. ... Robinson, who missed his third straight game with tightness in his lower back, didn't make the trip to Minneapolis. Popovich said he would rejoin the team sometime before the All-Star break. ... The Wolves have won seven of nine at home against the Spurs.
